### Threadgroup memory: the on-chip scratchpad

Threadgroup memory is shared across all threads of a single threadgroup, lives on-chip, and is roughly an order of magnitude faster than main memory. Use it whenever multiple threads need the same data.

The blur kernel rewritten to load each input element exactly once per threadgroup:

```cpp
kernel void blur1d_tg(
    device const float* a    [[buffer(0)]],
    device float* out         [[buffer(1)]],
    constant uint& n          [[buffer(2)]],
    uint gid                  [[thread_position_in_grid]],
    uint lid                  [[thread_position_in_threadgroup]],
    uint group_dim            [[threads_per_threadgroup]])
{
    threadgroup float tile[256 + 2];   // group_size + 2 halo cells

    // Each thread loads one element
    int loc = int(lid) + 1;
    tile[loc] = (gid < n) ? a[gid] : 0.0f;

    // Threads 0 and group_dim-1 also load the halos
    if (lid == 0) {
        int left = int(gid) - 1;
        tile[0] = (left >= 0) ? a[left] : a[gid];
    }
    if (lid == group_dim - 1 || gid == n - 1) {
        int right = int(gid) + 1;
        tile[loc + 1] = (right < int(n)) ? a[right] : a[gid];
    }

    threadgroup_barrier(mem_flags::mem_threadgroup);

    if (gid >= n) return;
    out[gid] = (tile[loc - 1] + tile[loc] + tile[loc + 1]) * (1.0f / 3.0f);
}
```

Launch with `group_size=256`. Each main-memory element is read at most twice (once by the body, once as a halo), versus three times in the naive version. On bandwidth-bound kernels that compounds quickly.

### `threadgroup_barrier`

The Metal equivalent of CUDA's `__syncthreads()`. The flag tells the compiler which memory orderings to enforce:

- `mem_flags::mem_threadgroup` — synchronize threadgroup memory only (most common).
- `mem_flags::mem_device` — also synchronize device-memory writes (rare; needed when threads read what other threads just wrote to global).
- `mem_flags::mem_none` — control-flow-only barrier.

Missing a barrier is a classic source of nondeterministic bugs: tests pass once, fail twice, pass when you add a print. Always pair `threadgroup` writes with a barrier before reads.

### Simdgroup operations

Within a simdgroup (32 threads, lockstep), Apple exposes a family of fast intra-warp primitives. The ones you'll use most:

| Function | What it does |
|---|---|
| `simd_sum(x)` | sum of `x` across the 32 lanes; broadcast to all |
| `simd_max(x)` / `simd_min(x)` | reduction, broadcast |
| `simd_shuffle(x, lane)` | every lane reads `x` from `lane` |
| `simd_shuffle_xor(x, mask)` | butterfly shuffle (canonical reduction pattern) |
| `simd_broadcast(x, lane)` | broadcast lane's value |
| `simd_prefix_inclusive_sum(x)` | inclusive scan within the simdgroup |

A fast block reduction using `simd_sum` plus a single threadgroup pass:

```cpp
kernel void block_sum(
    device const float* a   [[buffer(0)]],
    device float* out        [[buffer(1)]],
    constant uint& n         [[buffer(2)]],
    uint gid                 [[thread_position_in_grid]],
    uint lid                 [[thread_position_in_threadgroup]],
    uint sg_id               [[simdgroup_index_in_threadgroup]],
    uint sg_lane             [[thread_index_in_simdgroup]],
    uint sgs_per_tg          [[simdgroups_per_threadgroup]],
    uint tg_id               [[threadgroup_position_in_grid]])
{
    threadgroup float partials[32];   // up to 32 simdgroups per threadgroup

    float v = (gid < n) ? a[gid] : 0.0f;
    float sg_total = simd_sum(v);     // 1 instruction, no shared mem

    if (sg_lane == 0) partials[sg_id] = sg_total;
    threadgroup_barrier(mem_flags::mem_threadgroup);

    if (sg_id == 0) {
        float v2 = (sg_lane < sgs_per_tg) ? partials[sg_lane] : 0.0f;
        float total = simd_sum(v2);
        if (sg_lane == 0) out[tg_id] = total;
    }
}
```

This is the canonical "two-stage reduce" pattern, and it is essentially identical to the CUDA warp-shuffle version that closes Module 8 of the CUDA course.

### Simdgroup matrix (M3+)

M3 and later expose `simdgroup_matrix` types — Apple's analogue to NVIDIA tensor cores, accessed through `simdgroup_multiply_accumulate`. They unlock high-throughput fp16/bf16 GEMMs from custom kernels. The API is more constrained than tensor-core PTX but follows the same load-fragment / matmul / store-fragment pattern. A full GEMM is beyond this module's scope; the takeaway is that on M3+ you can get within ~70–80% of the MPSGraph matmul kernel from hand-written MSL.

> **Gotcha.** `simd_*` intrinsics assume **all 32 lanes are active**. Calling them inside a divergent branch where some lanes have early-returned gives undefined results. Always make sure the simdgroup is convergent before a simd-wide op (typical pattern: load with a guard, then unconditionally call `simd_sum` with zero for out-of-range lanes, as the kernel above does).

